ipfstat(8)                                             ipfstat(8)



NNAAMMEE
       ipfstat  -  reports on packet filter statistics and filter
       list

SSYYNNOOPPSSIISS
       iippffssttaatt [ --66aaAAffgghhIIiinnoossvv ] [ --dd <device> ]

       iippffssttaatt --tt [ --CC ] [ --DD <addrport> ] [ --PP <protocol> ] [ --SS
       <addrport> ] [ --TT <refresh time> ] [ --dd <device> ]

DDEESSCCRRIIPPTTIIOONN
       iippffssttaatt  examines  /dev/kmem  using the symbols __ffrr__ffllaaggss,
       __ffrrssttaattss, __ffiilltteerriinn, and __ffiilltteerroouutt.  To run and work,  it
       needs  to  be  able  to read both /dev/kmem and the kernel
       itself.  The kernel name defaults to //vvmmuunniixx.

       The default behaviour of iippffssttaatt is to retrieve  and  dis-
       play  the  accumulated  statistics which have been accumu-
       lated over time as the kernel has put packets through  the
       filter.

OOPPTTIIOONNSS
       --66     Display filter lists for IPv6, if available.

       --aa     Display  the  accounting filter list and show bytes
              counted against each rule.

       --AA     Display packet authentication statistics.

       --CC     This option is only valid in combination  with  --tt.
              Display  "closed"  states  as well in the top. Nor-
              mally, a TCP connection is not  displayed  when  it
              reaches  the  CLOSE_WAIT  protocol state. With this
              option enabled, all state entries are displayed.

       --dd <device>
              Use a device other than  //ddeevv//iippll  for  interfacing
              with the kernel.

       --DD <addrport>
              This  option  is only valid in combination with --tt.
              Limit the state top  display  to  show  only  state
              entries whose destination IP address and port match
              the addport argument. The addrport specification is
              of  the  form  ipaddress[,port].  The ipaddress and
              port should be either numerical or the string "any"
              (specifying  any ip address resp. any port). If the
              --DD option is not  specified,  it  defaults  to  "--DD
              any,any".

       --ff     Show  fragment  state  information (statistics) and
              held state information (in the kernel)  if  any  is
              present.

       --gg     Show  groups  currently configured (both active and
              inactive).

       --hh     Show per-rule the number of times each one scores a
              "hit".  For use in combination with --ii.

       --ii     Display  the filter list used for the input side of
              the kernel IP processing.

       --II     Swap between retrieving "inactive"/"active"  filter
              list details.  For use in combination with --ii.

       --nn     Show  the  "rule  number"  for  each  rule as it is
              printed.

       --oo     Display the filter list used for the output side of
              the kernel IP processing.

       --PP <protocol>
              This  option  is only valid in combination with --tt.
              Limit the state top  display  to  show  only  state
              entries  that  match a specific protocol. The argu-
              ment  can  be  a  protocol  name  (as  defined   in
              //eettcc//pprroottooccoollss)  or  a  protocol  number.  If  this
              option is not specified, state entries for any pro-
              tocol are specified.

       --ss     Show   packet/flow  state  information  (statistics
              only).

       --ssll    Show held state information (in the kernel) if  any
              is present (no statistics).

       --SS <addrport>
              This  option  is only valid in combination with --tt.
              Limit the state top  display  to  show  only  state
              entries  whose source IP address and port match the
              addport argument. The addrport specification is  of
              the  form ipaddress[,port].  The ipaddress and port
              should be either  numerical  or  the  string  "any"
              (specifying  any ip address resp. any port). If the
              --SS option is not  specified,  it  defaults  to  "--SS
              any,any".

       --tt     Show  the  state table in a way similar to they way
              ttoopp((11)) shows  the  process  table.  States  can  be
              sorted  using  a  number  of  different  ways. This
              options requires nnccuurrsseess((33)) and needs  to  be  com-
              piled  in. It may not be available on all operating
              systems. See below, for  more  information  on  the
              keys that can be used while ipfstat is in top mode.

       --TT <refreshtime>
              This option is only valid in combination  with  --tt.
              Specifies how often the state top display should be
              updated. The refresh time is the number of  seconds
              between an update. Any postive integer can be used.
              The default (and minimal update time) is 1.

       --vv     Turn verbose  mode  on.   Displays  more  debugging
              information.

SSYYNNOOPPSSIISS
       The  role  of iippffssttaatt is to display current kernel statis-
       tics gathered as a result of applying the filters in place
       (if  any) to packets going in and out of the kernel.  This
       is the default operation when no command  line  parameters
       are present.

       When  supplied  with either --ii or --oo, it will retrieve and
       display the appropriate list  of  filter  rules  currently
       installed and in use by the kernel.

SSTTAATTEE TTOOPP
       Using the --tt option iippffssttaatt will enter the state top mode.
       In this mode the state table is displayed similar  to  the
       way ttoopp displays the process table. The --CC, --DD, --PP, --SS and
       --TT commandline options can be used to restrict  the  state
       entries that will be shown and to specify the frequency of
       display updates.

       In state top mode, the  following  keys  can  be  used  to
       influence the displayed information:

       dd select information to display.

       ll redraw the screen.

       qq quit the program.

       ss switch between different sorting criterion.

       rr reverse the sorting criterion.

       States  can  be sorted by protocol number, by number of IP
       packets, by number of bytes and  by  time-to-live  of  the
       state  entry.  The  default  is  to  sort by the number of
       bytes. States are sorted in descending order, but you  can
       use the rr key to sort them in ascending order.

SSTTAATTEE TTOOPP LLIIMMIITTAATTIIOONNSS
       It  is  currently not possible to interactively change the
       source, destination and protocol  filters  or  the  refreh
       frequency. This must be done from the command line.

       The  screen must have at least 80 columns. This is however
       not checked.

       Only the first X-5 entries that match the sort and  filter
       criteria  are  displayed (where X is the number of rows on
       the display. There is no way to see more entries.

       No support for IPv6


FFIILLEESS
       /dev/kmem
       /dev/ipl
       /dev/ipstate
       /vmunix

SSEEEE AALLSSOO
       ipf(8)

BBUUGGSS
       none known.



